WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:05.040
SHANNON: She's a fourth
generation Argentine vintner

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:11.080
and an emergency physician in
San Francisco at UCSF and CPMC

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:12.820
Children's Hospital.

00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:15.880
She grew up in Argentina during
the military dictatorship,

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:17.750
finished high school
in the East Bay,

00:00:17.750 --> 00:00:21.970
and studied biology at Harvard
and medicine at Stanford.

00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:25.210
Today, she's managing director
of her family winery, Bodega

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:28.630
Catena Zapata, and makes
her own wines in Argentina

00:00:28.630 --> 00:00:32.590
under the Luca label, and is a
practicing emergency physician

00:00:32.590 --> 00:00:36.010
in San Francisco
at CPMC and UCSF.

00:00:36.010 --> 00:00:39.620
She's the author of "Vino
Argentino, an Insider's Guide

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:42.150
to Wines and the Wine
Country of Argentina,"

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:45.440
which was published by Chronicle
Books at the end of 2010.

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:47.510
It's the first
English language book

00:00:47.510 --> 00:00:49.475
about Argentine food and wine.

00:00:49.475 --> 00:00:51.629
With that, I'll turn
it over to Laura.

00:00:51.629 --> 00:00:53.420
LAURA CATENA: Thank
you very much, Shannon.

00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:56.840
I think I'm speaking with this.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:58.590
I feel like I don't
to say anything now,

00:00:58.590 --> 00:00:59.600
but thank you very much.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.130
Shannon.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:04.200
So today we're going to talk
a little bit about my book,

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:07.550
"Vino Argentino," about
Argentina, my country, my wine

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.830
region, Mendoza, a
little bit about Malbec,

00:01:10.830 --> 00:01:13.450
a little bit about my
family's 100-year-old history

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:19.560
making wine, and also I'll share
a bit of my personal story.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:25.120
These are the main principles
that we live by at our winery.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:26.170
Compete with the best.

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:28.720
Although we are in a
developing country,

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:31.500
we try to make
wines that can stand

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:33.160
with the best of the world.

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:34.350
Be academic.

00:01:34.350 --> 00:01:37.440
When we don't know something,
we study, we do research,

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.600
and we're humble about what we
know and what we don't know.

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.600
And believe fiercely
in what we do,

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:47.100
so that others will
also believe in us.

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:50.830
So this is my father,
Nicolas Catena and my uncle,

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:53.290
Jorge and my tia, Silvia.

00:01:53.290 --> 00:01:57.650
My father grew up in a very
tiny village in Mendoza.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.580
And at the age of
five, he started

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:03.030
working in the vineyard
with his father.

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:06.650
At the age of five, my kids were
working on their PlayStation

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:08.990
skills, like probably
some of you were.

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:14.440
This is my great-grandfather,
Nicola Catena,

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:18.710
that came to Argentina
from Italy in 1898

00:02:18.710 --> 00:02:21.230
with the dream of planting
a vineyard of his own.

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:25.490
I imagine some of you, your
parents, your grandparents,

00:02:25.490 --> 00:02:30.310
immigrated to the United
States with great dreams.

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:33.350
And this is my grandmother,
Angelica Zapata.

00:02:33.350 --> 00:02:36.100
We have a vineyard and
a wine named after her.

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:37.780
And unfortunately,
I never met her

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:41.510
because she died in a car
accident when my father was 18.

00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:45.150
But she is a very important
part of our family folklore.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.680
She was the headmaster
of the local school.

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:51.150
And she was a very tough
mother, according to my father.

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:54.360
And she believed
that education was

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:57.960
the way to progress and
to improving our society.

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:01.854
And she was known to go
get kids at their home

00:03:01.854 --> 00:03:02.770
if they missed school.

00:03:02.770 --> 00:03:05.061
Because many times, the
parents would keep them at home

00:03:05.061 --> 00:03:06.181
so that they would work.

00:03:06.181 --> 00:03:07.930
And she would actually
drive to the house,

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:12.000
sometimes even pay the parents
and bring the kid to school.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And my father tells a story of
when he was 18 years old, right

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.870
before she died, and
he went to her saying

00:03:17.870 --> 00:03:20.400
that he wanted to study
physics, and said to her,

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:22.640
what should I do with
a degree in physics?

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:26.500
And she said, you should
try to win the Nobel Prize.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.880
And maybe you guys talk
about winning the Nobel Prize

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:34.230
at Google, but he was a child
in a very small village.

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:36.630
And to have this
sort of expectation

00:03:36.630 --> 00:03:39.120
explains a lot of
what happened after.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:44.200
And it also explains possibly
some of my childhood traumas.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:47.500
So this is actually
a framed copy

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:52.270
of a review from Robert
Parker's, the wine advocate.

00:03:52.270 --> 00:03:54.460
Does anybody know--
does everybody

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:55.640
know who is Robert Parker?

00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:58.910
So he's this very
famous wine reviewer.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:02.600
And he gave one of our
wines 98 plus points.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:05.020
And this was the first time
that an Argentine wine,

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:06.860
or a South American
wine actually,

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:08.330
had received such a high rating.

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:10.800
So I put it in a frame
for my winemaker.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:12.870
And the next day,
I came over and I

00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:14.660
saw that he'd crossed
it off and he said,

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:17.370
quiero cien, which
means, I want 100.

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:20.180
And at first I thought well,
this guy's a little ungrateful.

00:04:20.180 --> 00:04:21.920
And then I thought,
you know, no.

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:24.190
This is the kind of
person that will actually

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:25.970
make 100 point wine.

00:04:25.970 --> 00:04:30.060
Because he won't be happy
until he achieves the top.

00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:35.310
So Argentina is an
amazing country.

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:38.060
Those of you who've been
there or who were born there,

00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:40.190
know what a beautiful
place it is.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:42.070
We have monkeys in
the north, penguins

00:04:42.070 --> 00:04:45.010
in the south, beautiful
plains with cattle.

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:46.840
We are one of the
largest producers

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:47.930
of soybean in the world.

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:49.010
We have tango.

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:51.340
We're my tango dancer?

00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:54.130
We have such incredible
culture there.

00:04:54.130 --> 00:04:57.720
But it's also a country
with an incredible economic

00:04:57.720 --> 00:04:58.930
instability.

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:03.170
So during my childhood, this
is what inflation looked like.

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:05.890
So imagine living
in a country where

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:09.880
you have 30, 40, 50,
3,000% inflation.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:12.830
And one thing I remember as
a child is that you always

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:15.070
spent your money,
because you never

00:05:15.070 --> 00:05:19.380
knew how much it would
be worth a week later.

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:21.230
And believe me,
it's very difficult.

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:23.550
Currently, the inflation
rate is about 30%.

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:27.200
And it's not easy to do
business in this environment.

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:29.420
And it's also a
country where there's

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:31.600
been a lot of political turmoil.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:34.980
During my childhood, there
were two military coups.

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:39.460
And more recently in 2001,
we had riots in the streets.

00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:42.420
And we had five
presidents in one week.

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:44.700
These are all the presidents.

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:46.370
We currently have
a female president.

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:55.660
So in the late
'70s, we were living

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.810
in a militarized country.

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:01.760
And my father had to negotiate
the release of my uncle

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:02.630
by kidnappers.

00:06:02.630 --> 00:06:04.900
He had been kept in
a closet for a week.

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:06.860
And my brother and
I had been sent

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:09.110
to a boarding school
in the countryside.

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.210
And it wasn't like the
fancy boarding schools

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:12.090
that you have here.

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:14.730
It was really in a village
in the countryside.

00:06:14.730 --> 00:06:16.584
And when I was 10
years old-- I was

00:06:16.584 --> 00:06:18.500
five when I started--
when I was 10 years old,

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.000
I was once sitting
in a classroom

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.860
and some guys in big
military gear kicked the door

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:25.770
and pointed guns at us.

00:06:25.770 --> 00:06:27.350
And the reason
they were there was

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:30.120
because they thought that
there were [INAUDIBLE], which

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:33.769
is our word for terrorist,
hiding in our school.

00:06:33.769 --> 00:06:35.060
And our school was closed down.

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:36.910
We came back to Buenos Aires.

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:38.830
And at that time,
my father decided

00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:41.530
to take a sabbatical
in Berkeley.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:43.580
And the one thing I
wanted to talk about,

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:46.360
and recently I was reading
a book called "I Am Malala."

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:48.810
I don't if any of
you have read it.

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:50.950
Anybody here read "I Am Malala?"

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:54.560
It's a book about this
young girl in Pakistan

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:56.930
who is shot by the Taliban.

00:06:56.930 --> 00:06:59.740
And she has this horrible
story of how she's shot.

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:03.020
But most of the book is
this joyful celebration

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:06.890
of living in this country where
there's bombs and shootings.

00:07:06.890 --> 00:07:10.200
But she celebrates her life
with family and friends.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.930
And actually, when my father
said we were leaving Argentina,

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:15.110
I was very upset, because
I was very happy there,

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:17.310
despite all the
things are happening.

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:20.050
But I was dragged to Berkeley.

00:07:20.050 --> 00:07:23.300
And there's a picture of
our family in Berkeley.

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:26.560
This is my father holding my
baby sister who was born there,

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:29.060
my mother, myself, and
my older brother who

00:07:29.060 --> 00:07:30.880
went off to college.

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:35.140
And my father was a visiting
scholar at UC Berkeley.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:36.760
But more importantly,
what he learned

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:39.040
about was this incredible
revolution that

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.390
was going on in the Napa Valley.

00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:43.850
These crazy
Californians were saying

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:47.210
that they were going to make
wines in California that

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:49.500
could compete with
the best French wines.

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:52.400
And I just want to take a little
survey of the room, who here

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:55.870
thinks that California
can make wine that's

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:57.780
as good as the
best French wines?

00:07:57.780 --> 00:07:59.210
Can we see some arms?

00:07:59.210 --> 00:07:59.710
OK.

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:01.250
Who thinks, and
you guys, there's

00:08:01.250 --> 00:08:03.890
no military regime at
Google, I understand.

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:08.010
Who here thinks that the
top French wines are still

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:09.924
the best in the world?

00:08:09.924 --> 00:08:10.810
Oh, yeah.

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:11.740
We got one.

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:12.510
Excellent.

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:13.310
[INAUDIBLE]

00:08:13.310 --> 00:08:14.430
Good for you.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:18.420
So anyhow, the Californians
have done a good job

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:19.930
at convincing people.

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:23.950
But at that time, for my father
to hear this was revolutionary.

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:27.330
Because he had grown up
in a world where you never

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:31.020
challenged the French, where
they dominated fine wine,

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:33.840
and where he could never
imagine that somebody

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.559
could compete with them.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:39.000
And then he heard about
the Judgment of Paris.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.270
Have any of you seen the
movie "Bottle Shock?"

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:46.430
So basically, this was a tasting
ran by an English man, Steven

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:49.130
Spurrier, right here, with
a bunch of French judges,

00:08:49.130 --> 00:08:51.890
where they compared--
it was in 1976-- they

00:08:51.890 --> 00:08:55.510
compared California wine
against French wine.

00:08:55.510 --> 00:08:57.800
Does anybody know
who won the tasting?

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:59.580
Anybody?

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:00.080
?

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:01.250
Yes?

00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:03.830
Chateau Montelena for
the chardonnay and Stag's

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:05.590
Leap for the Cabernet Sauvignon.

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:07.940
And actually, the
French people are still

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:10.370
denying that this
tasting ever happened.

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:12.880
But the Americans were
smart and made a movie.

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:16.170
So that proves everything.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.170
So my father went
back to Argentina.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:22.090
And he said, if the
Californians can do it,

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:26.010
why not me in Argentina.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:27.300
And this is just a side line.

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:30.890
While my father was planning
this revolution in Argentina,

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:34.626
I was actually perfecting
the Berkeley hippie look.

00:09:34.626 --> 00:09:37.150
I thought that was pretty good.

00:09:37.150 --> 00:09:38.800
I had a good time in Berkeley.

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:41.520
Anybody here live in Berkeley?

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:42.020
You guys?

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:42.786
Yeah?

00:09:42.786 --> 00:09:44.020
It's a great place.

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:49.070
So why was what my father was
trying to do so difficult?

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:52.470
At that time, South
America was equivalent

00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:54.310
with cheap Chilean wine.

00:09:54.310 --> 00:09:56.580
And you guys seem kind
of young, so you may not

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:59.120
have been drinking wine.

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:02.360
This is the mid '80s.

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:06.300
And at that time, South
America was cheap wine.

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:08.910
And most people in
Argentina were saying,

00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:10.520
we need to do what
Chile's doing.

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:11.870
They're doing very well with it.

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:14.150
We should go along with
what they're doing.

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:16.790
And when my father
said to his colleagues,

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:18.696
I want to make these
wines that can stand

00:10:18.696 --> 00:10:21.120
with the best of the world,
they said first of all,

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:22.420
we don't know if it's possible.

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.220
But even if you
made those wines,

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:28.350
no one will believe
that they're good.

00:10:28.350 --> 00:10:31.460
But my father was
not easily dissuaded.

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:34.410
And I want to talk a
little bit about what

00:10:34.410 --> 00:10:35.910
I call the academic approach.

00:10:35.910 --> 00:10:39.580
This is actually my father
and my sister, Adrianna,

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:41.830
she was the baby in
the Berkeley picture.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:46.470
She's getting a PhD in medieval
history at Oxford University.

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:51.310
And I was in the car with my
sister, telling her, you know,

00:10:51.310 --> 00:10:54.410
I think it's funny when
dad talks about your thesis

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:56.660
as if he knows as much
as you do about it.

00:10:56.660 --> 00:10:59.750
And my sister said, well he
actually knows more than I do.

00:10:59.750 --> 00:11:03.240
And my father is the kind of
person that loves to learn.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:05.800
And any time he sets his mind
to learning something new,

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:06.640
he does.

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.230
And actually here, my sister's
put him to work at the archives

00:11:10.230 --> 00:11:13.970
in [INAUDIBLE], studying
medieval Spanish history.

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:15.690
So this kind of
academic approach

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:18.290
is what he applied
to figuring out

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:22.750
how to make these
wines in Argentina.

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:25.640
And the first thing
he did was hire

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:27.270
some well-known consultants.

00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:29.220
And his first
consultant was a guy

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:31.580
from California
named Paul Hobbs.

00:11:31.580 --> 00:11:34.260
Has anybody had
Paul Hobb's wines?

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:35.020
Yeah.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:37.560
Yeah, so he's a very
talented winemaker.

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:39.100
He had made wine in France.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:41.200
He was making wine
in California.

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:43.640
And when he came
to Argentina, we

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:46.250
worked on how could
we go from the bottom

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:48.110
up to make these wines.

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:50.130
And the way wines
were being made

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:52.400
in Argentina at that
time was in what

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:55.820
we call the Italian
oxidative method.

00:11:55.820 --> 00:11:57.940
And what we would do is
we would press the grapes.

00:11:57.940 --> 00:12:01.770
And we would put them in these
huge old French oak barriques.

00:12:01.770 --> 00:12:03.960
And the wines would
receive oxygen.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:06.370
And what happens when
a wine gets oxygen

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:09.080
is that it loses its
characteristics, its flavors.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:11.820
So imagine that you
leave a bottle out

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.510
on the countertop for five days.

00:12:13.510 --> 00:12:14.629
You drink it.

00:12:14.629 --> 00:12:15.920
It doesn't taste like anything.

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:17.045
Everything tastes the same.

00:12:17.045 --> 00:12:18.680
And that's how wine
was being made.

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:22.050
So he realized that he
had to change everything

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:25.310
from the vineyard, studying the
terroir, the soil, the climate,

00:12:25.310 --> 00:12:28.230
and the winery, we were the
first to bring to Argentina

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:32.090
small French oak barriques,
and also the plant sources.

00:12:32.090 --> 00:12:35.130
So if you-- does anybody
have a little vineyard

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:37.590
in their backyard here?

00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:38.140
There you go.

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:40.860
So if you want to
plant your vineyard,

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:43.580
you go to a vine nursery
and you buy some plants.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:46.620
And you ask for A quality
plants, B quality plants,

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:47.640
C quality plants.

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:50.580
A quality is small
production high quality.

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:55.780
C quality is high yielding,
maybe not as interesting.

00:12:55.780 --> 00:12:57.760
So what my father
did is he started

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:03.250
bringing some of these top
level, high quality, plant

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:05.560
selections to Argentina
for the first time.

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:10.770
And I'm going to explain
to you in a minute why

00:13:10.770 --> 00:13:13.360
I'm having a light
saber fight here.

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:16.400
But first of all, I want to
talk about Jacques Luton who

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:20.820
is Darth Vader here, who
was our French consultant.

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:24.990
And has anybody had any of
the Luton wines from France?

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:27.630
So has anybody had Chavel Blanc?

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:29.790
So Chavel Blanc is
a very famous wine.

00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:33.270
And Jacques's cousin is the
winemaker at Chavel Blanc.

00:13:33.270 --> 00:13:35.900
And they're this very well
known Bourdeaux family

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:37.380
that make wine.

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:41.460
And my father, when I was
still at Harvard undergrad,

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:45.030
invited me to go with him
to France as his translator.

00:13:45.030 --> 00:13:46.850
And we went to see Jacques.

00:13:46.850 --> 00:13:50.050
And we brought a bottle of
some Cabernet Sauvignon,

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:54.250
this is in the late '80s,
of some Cabernet Sauvignon

00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:58.500
from one of the traditional
areas in Argentina in the east.

00:13:58.500 --> 00:14:00.109
And we brought this
bottle of wine.

00:14:00.109 --> 00:14:01.150
And we poured it for him.

00:14:01.150 --> 00:14:04.050
I remember we were in
this very fancy chateau.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:06.460
I was so impressed
by everything.

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:09.382
And he said, Nicola [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:09.382 --> 00:14:11.930
This is a very nice
Cabernet Sauvignon.

00:14:11.930 --> 00:14:15.446
Like one from the [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:15.446 --> 00:14:18.700
And I heard this, and I thought
oh, that sounds wonderful.

00:14:18.700 --> 00:14:21.350
And then my father
was very serious.

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:23.760
And I said, what's going on.

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:26.190
And he said this is
the worst insult.

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:28.010
This would be like
somebody saying

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:29.950
this tastes like a
very nice Cabernet

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:31.820
from the Central Valley.

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:33.855
So anyhow, so we have
this opportunity.

00:14:33.855 --> 00:14:36.200
Jacques and I were
both invited to what

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.580
was called the Jedi Tour
by our importer in Canada.

00:14:39.580 --> 00:14:40.920
And I said, let's have some fun.

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:43.980
Let's have a light saber fight.

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:46.000
And I said, but I
have to kill you

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.940
at the end in revenge for
what you said to us, to my dad

00:14:49.940 --> 00:14:52.120
and I. Because now he
thinks we make great wine.

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:55.560
But anyhow, the main concept
that came from Jacques

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.985
was about cool climate.

00:14:57.985 --> 00:14:59.890
And this could have
been a death sentence.

00:14:59.890 --> 00:15:02.090
Because maybe we didn't
have any cool climate.

00:15:02.090 --> 00:15:04.520
But we were fortunate
that as you go up

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:08.320
towards the mountains, it gets
colder and colder and colder.

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:11.850
So we actually had a
location with cooler climate

00:15:11.850 --> 00:15:14.910
within our region.

00:15:14.910 --> 00:15:17.880
So this is my grandfather,
who I call Nonno.

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:21.210
That's what you call your
grandfather in Italian.

00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:24.250
And the slide is
named Why Malbec?

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:28.520
So my grandfather used to do to
France and Italy, and come back

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:31.950
and say to my dad,
Nicolas, you're

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:34.175
paying way too much attention
to Cabernet Sauvignon

00:15:34.175 --> 00:15:35.240
and chardonnay.

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:37.610
The greatest variety
that we have is Malbec.

00:15:37.610 --> 00:15:39.660
And my father wasn't
sure, because most

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:43.450
of the Malbecs he tasted back
then weren't that interesting.

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:46.000
But then in the late '80s,
my grandfather passed away

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.510
and my dad got a little
sentimental, said you know,

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:50.820
I got to try this.

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:52.330
It got to do this for my father.

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:55.060
And the interesting thing
when I was working on my book,

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:57.860
I did a lot of
research on Malbec.

00:15:57.860 --> 00:16:01.920
And actually, Malbec was one of
the most prestigious varieties

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:05.040
in France in the Middle Ages
and in the 19th century.

00:16:05.040 --> 00:16:07.240
In the Middle Ages, it
was called the black wine.

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:09.930
And actually it was drank
and the wedding of Eleanor

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:12.690
of Acquitaine and also
is famous in the court

00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:14.760
of Peter the Great.

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:19.520
And then in Bordeaux, in
the 19th century, 40 to 60%

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:22.510
of the first growths,
all these famous wines,

00:16:22.510 --> 00:16:25.510
first, second, third growth,
the grand crus from France

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:26.700
had Malbec in them.

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:28.820
But the French don't
like to talk about it.

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:31.010
Because now they replace
the Malbec with Merlot,

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:33.910
so they don't want to
make the Malbec famous.

00:16:33.910 --> 00:16:38.480
But this was a variety with a
very good pedigree in quality

00:16:38.480 --> 00:16:39.480
and also in ageability.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.610
So this is the
Adrianna Vineyard,

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:45.920
named after my sister.

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:48.670
And so what my
father did at first

00:16:48.670 --> 00:16:51.610
was to study the
climate and the soil.

00:16:51.610 --> 00:16:54.040
And he put weather
stations all over Mendoza.

00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:57.130
This took about 10 years
to do all this research.

00:16:57.130 --> 00:16:59.440
And he found this
place in Gualtallary

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:00.730
in a place called Tupungato.

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:02.739
Have you heard of
the Uco Valley?

00:17:02.739 --> 00:17:04.780
So the Uco Valley is where
some very high quality

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:05.960
wines come in Argentina.

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:07.560
And this was a vineyard.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.319
Kelsey, your mother's
vineyard's in the Uco Valley.

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:12.263
Yeah, we have somebody
with a vineyard

00:17:12.263 --> 00:17:14.960
in the family in the Uco valley.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:17.880
So he went to this place.

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:20.150
He put these weather stations .

00:17:20.150 --> 00:17:23.410
And this place was
as cold as Burgundy.

00:17:23.410 --> 00:17:25.652
Has anybody here
been to Burgundy?

00:17:25.652 --> 00:17:26.910
A few people, yeah.

00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:30.590
So Burgundy, you would never
ever plant Malbec in Burgundy.

00:17:30.590 --> 00:17:32.520
Because Malbec is
a Bordeaux variety.

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:33.890
And it would be too cold.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:36.110
But my father thought,
hey it's cold.

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:37.680
But it's very sunny.

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:40.570
So Malbec might ripen there.

00:17:40.570 --> 00:17:42.505
And it did.

00:17:42.505 --> 00:17:44.630
And you're going to get to
taste some of the Malbec

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:46.587
from Adrianna.

00:17:46.587 --> 00:17:48.420
So he planted this
vineyard despite the fact

00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:50.460
that all his
viticulturalists said

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:52.530
grapes will never ripen here.

00:17:52.530 --> 00:17:54.262
But they did.

00:17:54.262 --> 00:17:55.720
And then the next
thing that he had

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:57.800
to work on what the
plant selection.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:00.520
Because you could go to the
divine nurseries in France

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:04.040
and get fantastic cuttings
for Cabernet or chardonnay.

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:06.090
But you couldn't get
good quality Malbec.

00:18:06.090 --> 00:18:07.630
So he went to our
oldest vineyard

00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:11.330
which is named Angelica
after my grandmother.

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:15.330
And he made a selection
of 145 different plans.

00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:18.770
And one important thing
to know about vines

00:18:18.770 --> 00:18:20.440
is that although
in the wild, they

00:18:20.440 --> 00:18:22.780
would reproduce by
seeds, if you were

00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:26.330
to plant the seed of
a grape, of Cabernet,

00:18:26.330 --> 00:18:28.440
the new plant would
not be Cabernet.

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:29.940
It would create a
different variety.

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:32.560
So if you want to plant
a Cabernet vineyard,

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:36.070
you actually use the
cuttings after pruning.

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:39.160
And a cutting from
one plant will

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:42.330
make another plant that's
exact to the mother plant.

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:46.230
And so he made a selection of
145 plants and studied them.

00:18:46.230 --> 00:18:48.690
And then, we call these
the Catena cuttings,

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:51.920
and we plant these cuttings
in all our vineyards.

00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:55.340
And this is just to
show you how different

00:18:55.340 --> 00:18:59.420
the grapes can be from
four different cuttings.

00:18:59.420 --> 00:19:01.670
So they're completely different.

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:03.800
And they have completely
different flavors.

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:04.870
But they are all Malbec.

00:19:07.970 --> 00:19:11.320
So this is my
mother, Elena Catena.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:16.890
So 10 years of research, we
now go from the early '80s

00:19:16.890 --> 00:19:20.680
to the late '80s, I
think it was about '91.

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:24.050
And my father has made some
wines, Cabernet, chardonnay,

00:19:24.050 --> 00:19:27.670
Malbec, that the consultants,
people who come down

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:31.620
to the winery say, wow, you've
hit a great level of quality.

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:35.380
But he has a big problem, which
is that he's a total geek.

00:19:35.380 --> 00:19:39.940
And he likes to spend time
in a library or alone.

00:19:39.940 --> 00:19:43.380
There might be some of you
like that, but maybe not.

00:19:43.380 --> 00:19:47.350
And he realizes that he
is not the right person

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:50.000
to go out to the world
and tell our story.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
And my mom was actually
running a high tech

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.200
company in Argentina back then.

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:56.840
And she went back actually to
running her high tech company.

00:19:56.840 --> 00:19:58.330
That's what she does now.

00:19:58.330 --> 00:20:02.330
But so my dad asked my mom
if she would go to the US

00:20:02.330 --> 00:20:03.940
and to Europe and
present our wines.

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:06.580
And just to tell you a little
bit about my mom's personality,

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:09.190
everybody in their
family has the parent

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:11.360
that arrives early to the
airport and the one that

00:20:11.360 --> 00:20:13.390
arrives late, right.

00:20:13.390 --> 00:20:16.370
And so obviously my dad
arrives about five hours early,

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:18.630
and my mom 30 minutes earlier.

00:20:18.630 --> 00:20:21.740
And so one time we were running
to the gate with my brother,

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:24.180
my mother, and I. And
we get to the gate.

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:25.960
And there is the pilot.

00:20:25.960 --> 00:20:28.370
And the plane is pulling off.

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:31.880
And my mom drops to her
knees and starts praying.

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:33.120
And the guy comes back.

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:34.560
And we get on the plane.

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:40.500
So my mom told me how this
went, her trip to the US.

00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:42.470
She said, Laurita,
that's what she calls me,

00:20:42.470 --> 00:20:44.930
I went to the store.

00:20:44.930 --> 00:20:46.350
I show them our wine.

00:20:46.350 --> 00:20:50.010
They said, I will not by an
Argentenian wine for $20.

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:51.480
And I said, OK, Give me.

00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:53.610
What is your best
wine in the store?

00:20:53.610 --> 00:20:54.985
And they would pull some wine.

00:20:54.985 --> 00:20:55.610
I would buy it.

00:20:55.610 --> 00:20:57.026
I would say, let's
taste it blind.

00:20:57.026 --> 00:21:01.160
And we always won the
blind competition.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.430
So my mother sold
one bottle at a time.

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:07.500
And we will always
be grateful to her,

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:11.150
because I don't think that
anybody else in our family

00:21:11.150 --> 00:21:12.210
could have done this.

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:18.960
So the New York Wine Experience.

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.690
This is why I'm here today.

00:21:20.690 --> 00:21:23.770
Because I went to
medical school.

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:27.500
I had absolutely no intention
of ever working for my family.

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:29.059
But it was the '90s.

00:21:29.059 --> 00:21:30.850
I had just finished
med school at Stanford.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:33.770
I was doing my residency
in emergency medicine.

00:21:33.770 --> 00:21:35.570
And my dad called
me and said, we've

00:21:35.570 --> 00:21:37.660
been invited to this
very prestigious thing.

00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:40.270
Has anybody been to the
New York Wine Experience?

00:21:40.270 --> 00:21:41.130
Oh, you have been.

00:21:41.130 --> 00:21:41.720
Great.

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:44.870
So the New York Wine Experience
is this amazing tasting

00:21:44.870 --> 00:21:47.770
where the Wine
Spectator invites some

00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:50.220
of the top winers of the world.

00:21:50.220 --> 00:21:51.290
It's kind of expensive.

00:21:51.290 --> 00:21:53.070
But you get to taste wines.

00:21:53.070 --> 00:21:55.430
Did you not think it was
incredible-- the wines?

00:21:55.430 --> 00:21:58.370
You get to taste wines that you
would never be able to taste.

00:21:58.370 --> 00:22:00.540
It would take you years to
go visit all those places

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:02.440
and to get that kind of quality.

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:05.720
You get old vintages from some
of the best wines in France,

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:07.550
and Italy, and all
over the world.

00:22:07.550 --> 00:22:08.540
So we were invited.

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:10.670
We were the first
Argentine winery

00:22:10.670 --> 00:22:13.000
to be invited to this tasting.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.650
And so I'm standing
in my little booth.

00:22:15.650 --> 00:22:18.000
And I'm watching these
big crowds standing

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.310
behind the Italian, the
Californian, the French.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:23.970
And this is what it
looked like at my stand.

00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:26.080
So people and walk by.

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:30.200
They'd kind of look over me
because I have heels now,

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:31.800
but normally I'm pretty short.

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:33.420
And so they would see Catena.

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:34.482
They would see Argentina.

00:22:34.482 --> 00:22:35.940
And they would make
no eye contact.

00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:37.224
They'd keep on walking.

00:22:37.224 --> 00:22:39.890
And what really pissed me off is
that some people would actually

00:22:39.890 --> 00:22:43.560
spit at my spittoon
somebody else's wine.

00:22:43.560 --> 00:22:45.460
And then they'd move on.

00:22:45.460 --> 00:22:49.490
So I had very few people
coming to my stand.

00:22:49.490 --> 00:22:50.900
And it made me so angry.

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:54.580
So the minute I got back to
California, I called my dad.

00:22:54.580 --> 00:22:55.884
And I said, I want in.

00:22:55.884 --> 00:22:57.050
I'm coming to work with you.

00:22:57.050 --> 00:22:57.870
I want to go to the winery.

00:22:57.870 --> 00:22:58.750
I want to go to the vineyards.

00:22:58.750 --> 00:23:00.380
I want to help you
sell the wines.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:02.940
Because I realized that
he needed some major help,

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:06.900
that what he was trying
to do was so difficult.

00:23:06.900 --> 00:23:08.140
This is important.

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:10.010
So I started
working with my dad.

00:23:10.010 --> 00:23:12.260
And I knew a lot
about wine tasting.

00:23:12.260 --> 00:23:13.530
And I tasted some great wines.

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:16.560
But I knew very little
of the wine lingo.

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:19.170
And I didn't really know which
varieties were from where.

00:23:19.170 --> 00:23:21.810
And this is actually one of
the first books that I read.

00:23:21.810 --> 00:23:24.100
And probably none of
you have read this book.

00:23:24.100 --> 00:23:25.260
But it's a great book.

00:23:25.260 --> 00:23:27.390
I highly recommend
it, especially

00:23:27.390 --> 00:23:30.150
if you've tasted a lot
but you kind of forget,

00:23:30.150 --> 00:23:31.780
oh what's the grape
from Piedmont?

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:33.830
And what's the grape
from this place?

00:23:33.830 --> 00:23:34.660
You read this book.

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:37.440
And you actually know
more than most winemakers

00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:39.760
about some of the
basics about wine.

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:42.490
So I highly recommend it.

00:23:42.490 --> 00:23:48.260
So when I went back, I realized
that all these consultants

00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:51.420
were giving us advice
about how to make

00:23:51.420 --> 00:23:53.990
great wine in other
parts of the world.

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:56.260
But our region was
completely different.

00:23:56.260 --> 00:24:00.550
There is no other region in the
world as high as our region.

00:24:00.550 --> 00:24:03.480
And also, they didn't know a
lot about Malbec wine making.

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:06.200
In fact, most of us would
tell us to make Malbec the way

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:07.410
you make Cabernet.

00:24:07.410 --> 00:24:10.490
And actually, you need to treat
Malbec totally differently.

00:24:10.490 --> 00:24:13.470
And they would also give
us advice like, you know,

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:14.950
in order to remove
green flavors,

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:17.170
you need to remove all
the leaves from the vines.

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:19.750
And actually, if you remove all
the leaves at high altitude,

00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:22.980
there's so much sunlight that
you get burning of the grapes.

00:24:22.980 --> 00:24:24.730
And you get pruney flavors.

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:25.964
And that's not what you want.

00:24:25.964 --> 00:24:27.630
So I realized that
we were going to have

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:30.680
to do our own research if we
wanted to improve quality.

00:24:30.680 --> 00:24:33.620
And that's why I founded
the Catena Institute that

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:36.350
does over 1,000
microvinifications per year.

00:24:36.350 --> 00:24:38.930
And we study everything
about our climate,

00:24:38.930 --> 00:24:40.800
high altitude, Malbec.

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:43.540
And also we study new
varieties, new regions,

00:24:43.540 --> 00:24:47.310
sort of whatever
we think is fun.

00:24:47.310 --> 00:24:49.660
This is one of the
studies that we did.

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:53.710
So this is the Angelica
vineyard at 2,700 elevation,

00:24:53.710 --> 00:24:55.900
La Piramide,
Adrianna, the vineyard

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:58.930
you saw the picture of,
5,000 feet elevation.

00:24:58.930 --> 00:25:01.750
You can see the
temperature is a lot lower.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:04.860
You go from 15, average
15 Celsius, to 12.

00:25:04.860 --> 00:25:07.960
This in viticulture
is a huge difference.

00:25:07.960 --> 00:25:10.850
And the sun is a
lot more intense.

00:25:10.850 --> 00:25:13.430
And we found that these
grapes at high altitude,

00:25:13.430 --> 00:25:16.630
and these are all the same
plant selections of Malbec,

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:19.790
had more than twice the amount
of tannins in the skins.

00:25:19.790 --> 00:25:23.690
And tannins are what give
you a flavor and ageability.

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:28.740
So we found that there was a
very big impact from altitude

00:25:28.740 --> 00:25:34.185
on great quality and also on
the kind of flavors we got.

00:25:34.185 --> 00:25:35.810
And this is a group
of our researchers.

00:25:35.810 --> 00:25:39.080
They're measuring
photosynthesis in the plants.

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:43.410
And I imagine you think that
wine research is, you just walk

00:25:43.410 --> 00:25:45.300
around with a glass
of wine and have fun.

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:46.810
But actually, it's
pretty hard work.

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:48.810
And there's a lot of sun.

00:25:48.810 --> 00:25:50.270
But it's still really fun.

00:25:52.860 --> 00:25:56.390
And this is a recent article
that we published about Malbec

00:25:56.390 --> 00:25:59.070
in "The American Journal of the
Viticulture and Technology."

00:25:59.070 --> 00:26:00.780
And this made me really proud.

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:02.810
This professor at
Davis said that it

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:06.430
was the largest of its
magnitude ever undertaken

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:09.650
of a single variety in multiple
countries and hemispheres.

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:12.240
And I was very proud
that our institute

00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:15.660
was able to publish in probably
the most reputable journal

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:17.300
and our industry.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:18.950
And this research
was done by our head

00:26:18.950 --> 00:26:21.910
of research, Fernando Buscema.

