00:27:43.290 --> 00:27:45.390
This is a map of our
Adrianna vineyard.

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:48.130
And it would probably take
me about an hour or two

00:27:48.130 --> 00:27:50.410
to explain this map.

00:27:50.410 --> 00:27:52.050
But I want to tell you a story.

00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:55.790
About 15 years ago, I was
at the Adrianna vineyard

00:27:55.790 --> 00:27:58.150
up there, almost
5,000 feet elevation.

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:01.124
And I was talking to the
viticulturist in charge.

00:28:01.124 --> 00:28:03.540
And I was seeing that there
was some areas of the vineyard

00:28:03.540 --> 00:28:05.373
that some browning that
didn't look so good.

00:28:05.373 --> 00:28:10.530
And I said, hey, what can we do
in these parts of the vineyard,

00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:14.024
because this is the vineyard
are we getting our best quality.

00:28:14.024 --> 00:28:16.440
And he said, you should take
a bulldozer to this vineyard.

00:28:16.440 --> 00:28:18.430
You should take
all the vines out.

00:28:18.430 --> 00:28:21.010
You should take all the
topsoil, mix it all up,

00:28:21.010 --> 00:28:22.140
and put it back on.

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:25.040
Because there's too much
diversity in this vineyard.

00:28:25.040 --> 00:28:28.130
And this really pissed
me off obviously,

00:28:28.130 --> 00:28:30.720
because I'm thinking this
is our best vineyard.

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:32.050
What are you talking about?

00:28:32.050 --> 00:28:34.580
But I kind of realized
talking to him

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:37.230
that we needed to go a lot
more micro in this vineyard,

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:39.950
that we needed to separate lots
and treat them all differently.

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:42.320
Not only in the vineyard,
but then in the winery.

00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:46.430
And based on that, we actually
changed our whole approach

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:50.630
to dividing our vineyards and
harvesting at different times.

00:28:50.630 --> 00:28:53.740
And this vineyard actually
this recent harvest

00:28:53.740 --> 00:28:57.020
was harvested in
137 different lots.

00:28:57.020 --> 00:28:59.120
There were all
harvested separately.

00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:02.800
Each lot was treated separately
and vinified separately.

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:06.340
So that's why you see so many
marks and things on this map.

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:10.260
And although this viticulturist
is no longer with us,

00:29:10.260 --> 00:29:12.310
I'm actually-- I
always remember him,

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:15.870
because he taught me something.

00:29:15.870 --> 00:29:17.700
And this is just for you to see.

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:20.750
You could have these three
completely different kinds

00:29:20.750 --> 00:29:23.690
of soils within this space.

00:29:23.690 --> 00:29:26.950
These are calcareous soils.

00:29:26.950 --> 00:29:29.080
They're also called
limestone soils.

00:29:29.080 --> 00:29:30.950
You might have heard
in Burgundy they

00:29:30.950 --> 00:29:32.402
have a lot of limestone soils.

00:29:32.402 --> 00:29:34.110
And they're considered
very high quality.

00:29:34.110 --> 00:29:36.340
We also like them
very much for Malbec.

00:29:36.340 --> 00:29:39.010
This is a deep soil that
has a little bit of clay,

00:29:39.010 --> 00:29:42.340
retains a little more
moisture, maybe a little better

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:45.360
for Cabernet which does
not like too much stress.

00:29:45.360 --> 00:29:49.730
And this is a stony soil, which
we love for Malbec, because it

00:29:49.730 --> 00:29:52.990
has excellent drainage and it
actually stresses the vine.

00:29:52.990 --> 00:29:56.580
And Malbec does very well
with a little bit of stress.

00:29:56.580 --> 00:30:00.010
We get great
quality with stress.

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:03.050
So this is our winemaker,
Alejandro Vigil.

00:30:03.050 --> 00:30:05.320
And I love this guy.

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:07.320
He's been working
with us since 2002,

00:30:07.320 --> 00:30:10.290
because he is, to me
the winemaker that I've

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:14.710
met that best mixes the art
and the science of wine making.

00:30:14.710 --> 00:30:16.540
And we actually
hired him when he

00:30:16.540 --> 00:30:18.380
was the head of
the soils division

00:30:18.380 --> 00:30:19.950
at the local
agriculture institute.

00:30:19.950 --> 00:30:21.770
And he first came in research.

00:30:21.770 --> 00:30:24.460
But then I realized that he
had such an amazing palette

00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:26.360
that he became our
head winemaker.

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:28.590
And he and I love
to taste together.

00:30:28.590 --> 00:30:34.190
And watching him taste,
what I realize every time

00:30:34.190 --> 00:30:37.640
is that there is no
chemical measurement that

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:40.530
can be better than
a good tongue.

00:30:40.530 --> 00:30:44.444
Because if you measure acidity,
if you measure alcohol,

00:30:44.444 --> 00:30:46.610
you can measure tannins,
there's all kinds of things

00:30:46.610 --> 00:30:48.210
that you can measure.

00:30:48.210 --> 00:30:52.470
But a good taster will
give you better information

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:56.197
about the quality of a wine that
any kind of chemical analysis.

00:30:56.197 --> 00:30:58.280
And that's why I love
working with him, because he

00:30:58.280 --> 00:30:59.654
has such an
extraordinary palate.

00:30:59.654 --> 00:31:02.360
And this is a
tattoo that he has.

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:04.850
And I love the story
about this tattoo.

00:31:04.850 --> 00:31:07.670
He was at a tasting in Brazil.

00:31:07.670 --> 00:31:09.830
And he had been invited
to this collector's house.

00:31:09.830 --> 00:31:10.110
Oh, yeah.

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:10.940
You're the Brazil guy.

00:31:10.940 --> 00:31:11.440
Yeah.

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:13.880
OK, so he was invited
to this tasting.

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:16.720
And this guy was opening one
amazing bottle after another.

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:18.220
And then the next
thing he remembers

00:31:18.220 --> 00:31:20.460
is he's in his
hotel room sleeping.

00:31:20.460 --> 00:31:21.410
He wakes up.

00:31:21.410 --> 00:31:23.025
And he's got this tattoo.

00:31:23.025 --> 00:31:24.250
It says Malbec.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:27.980
And fortunately, Juan
Cruz and not Rosita,

00:31:27.980 --> 00:31:30.010
because Juan Cruz is his son.

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:32.510
So that was OK with
his wife, Maria.

00:31:32.510 --> 00:31:36.760
But I love the story
about the tattoo.

00:31:36.760 --> 00:31:40.850
So here we are,
aspiring to make wines

00:31:40.850 --> 00:31:43.250
that can stand with
the best of the world.

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:47.210
And with the 1997 vintage of
the Nicolas Catena Zapata.

00:31:47.210 --> 00:31:50.232
And that's a wine that
I named after my father.

00:31:50.232 --> 00:31:51.190
It's a Cabernet Malbec.

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:53.990
That that's his favorite blend.

00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:55.130
I thought we were ready.

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:57.470
And my father agreed, although
he kept on backing off,

00:31:57.470 --> 00:32:00.460
that we were ready to do blind
tastings around the world,

00:32:00.460 --> 00:32:02.220
comparing our wines to others.

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:05.580
And this is actually a tasting
that was published online.

00:32:05.580 --> 00:32:11.590
We did this tasting in
London and look at the date.

00:32:11.590 --> 00:32:13.512
So it was September 10, 2001.

00:32:13.512 --> 00:32:14.970
So actually, none
of our winemakers

00:32:14.970 --> 00:32:17.230
could get back home
back after the tasting.

00:32:17.230 --> 00:32:20.870
But we did this tasting where we
compared to Latour, [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:20.870 --> 00:32:23.230
Caymus special
selection, Opus One.

00:32:23.230 --> 00:32:25.070
And we were mostly
hoping that we

00:32:25.070 --> 00:32:27.400
wouldn't be last in the tasting.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:28.980
But we actually came in first.

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:30.922
And people like
Jancis Robinson--

00:32:30.922 --> 00:32:32.630
does anybody know who
Jancis Robinson is?

00:32:32.630 --> 00:32:35.480
She's probably the most
famous female wine person.

00:32:35.480 --> 00:32:37.970
She organized the tasting.

00:32:37.970 --> 00:32:40.380
And there were many other
very good palates from England

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:40.910
there.

00:32:40.910 --> 00:32:42.097
And we came in first.

00:32:42.097 --> 00:32:43.430
There were three small tastings.

00:32:43.430 --> 00:32:44.767
We came in first.

00:32:44.767 --> 00:32:46.350
And the interesting
thing is that they

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:48.810
were supposed to write
which wine they thought

00:32:48.810 --> 00:32:50.820
was which wine.

00:32:50.820 --> 00:32:53.480
And nobody guessed that
our wine was our wine.

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:57.250
Because they could not imagine
that a wine from Argentina

00:32:57.250 --> 00:32:58.500
would be that good.

00:32:58.500 --> 00:33:00.280
And that was in 2001.

00:33:00.280 --> 00:33:06.050
And this is a little review that
Robert Parker's "Wine Advocate"

00:33:06.050 --> 00:33:07.480
that our importer prepared.

00:33:07.480 --> 00:33:10.250
And it was basically
comparing average ratings

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:13.100
from 2004 to 2009.

00:33:13.100 --> 00:33:15.500
These are some of
the top rated wines.

00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:20.870
And Romanee-Conti, I've only
had it once, it's about $10,000

00:33:20.870 --> 00:33:21.970
plus a bottle.

00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:23.840
Has anybody here had it?

00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:24.340
OK.

00:33:24.340 --> 00:33:28.010
So you have to find some rich
person to share it with you.

00:33:28.010 --> 00:33:31.060
That's-- or like my winemaker.

00:33:31.060 --> 00:33:32.920
Go to some collector's house.

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:34.460
So we're right after.

00:33:34.460 --> 00:33:37.210
And then you might know some of
these wines-- Harlan, Shafer,

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:40.320
Hillside Select,
Gaia, Chateaubriand.

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:42.480
So these are amazing reviews.

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:45.460
But the reality is
that people still

00:33:45.460 --> 00:33:48.330
don't know about
the kind of quality

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:49.810
we can get in Argentina.

