00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:48.250
AUDIENCE: It might
be a basic question.

00:39:48.250 --> 00:39:51.675
But I'm a very big fan of
Carmeneres and Malbecs.

00:39:51.675 --> 00:39:53.620
Why Carmenere never
makes to Argentina,

00:39:53.620 --> 00:39:55.930
Malbecs never make to Chile?

00:39:55.930 --> 00:39:57.790
LAURA CATENA: That's
a very good question.

00:39:57.790 --> 00:40:01.020
Well, Malbec-- actually,
I don't know the answer

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:03.760
to the question of why they
were brought initially.

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:07.440
So Malbec was brought
to Argentina in 1852.

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:10.600
And it came with many
of the French varieties.

00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:13.550
And actually, nobody
knows why Malbec

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:15.960
became the most important
variety in Argentina.

00:40:15.960 --> 00:40:19.910
My theory is that it adapted
so well to the climate.

00:40:19.910 --> 00:40:23.570
And I still think that Malbec
and Mendoza especially,

00:40:23.570 --> 00:40:26.070
are such a great
combination, because Malbec

00:40:26.070 --> 00:40:28.480
likes the sunlight, it
likes the kind of soils,

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:31.550
that I think that people
saw that it gave great wine.

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:33.470
And that's why they
kept on replanting it.

00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:36.510
And if you actually think of the
climate of Argentina and Chile,

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:38.590
they are more different
than the climate

00:40:38.590 --> 00:40:40.440
of Burgundy and Bordeaux.

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:42.460
Because we have these mountains.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:46.110
And we have this high
altitude, semi-desert.

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:48.010
And they have the
ocean influence.

00:40:48.010 --> 00:40:49.270
And they're much lower.

00:40:49.270 --> 00:40:51.690
So actually, the
soil and the climate

00:40:51.690 --> 00:40:53.830
are so different
that you would not

00:40:53.830 --> 00:40:57.026
expect the same varieties to
do well in both countries.

00:40:57.026 --> 00:40:58.400
So I think probably
what happened

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:01.210
is Carmenere did well there and
Malbec did well in Argentina.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.340
And then that became
a historic fact.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:04.280
But that's my theory.

00:41:04.280 --> 00:41:08.390
I don't actually know
the for sure answer.

00:41:08.390 --> 00:41:11.340
But great question-- I've
never been asked that before.

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:12.340
Yeah.

00:41:12.340 --> 00:41:14.840
AUDIENCE: Do you have to make
reservations so far in advance

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:16.381
when you're in
Argentina than in Napa

00:41:16.381 --> 00:41:17.892
and Chile and other places?

00:41:17.892 --> 00:41:18.600
LAURA CATENA: OK.

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:22.340
So the question is why is the
reservation system so formal

00:41:22.340 --> 00:41:25.680
in Argentina, and you have
to make reservations so far

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:26.986
in advance?

00:41:26.986 --> 00:41:29.360
Did you have a hard time making
reservation at my winery?

00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:29.957
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:41:29.957 --> 00:41:31.290
LAURA CATENA: You didn't get in?

00:41:31.290 --> 00:41:32.830
You know, I'll
tell you one story.

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:35.400
I once got in a
taxi in Argentina.

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:36.360
And I asked the guy.

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:37.420
He didn't know who I was.

00:41:37.420 --> 00:41:41.160
I said, where do you
take people wine tasting?

00:41:41.160 --> 00:41:43.655
And he says, oh this
winery, that winery.

00:41:43.655 --> 00:41:45.130
He's not mentioning my winery.

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:47.430
So I said, what
about Catena Zapata.

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:49.100
He said, oh I never
take them there.

00:41:49.100 --> 00:41:51.490
It's impossible to get
an appointment there.

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:53.350
And so I go back to my guy.

00:41:53.350 --> 00:41:55.300
And I say, open up more spots.

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:59.741
And actually we maximize
how many spots we have.

00:41:59.741 --> 00:42:01.490
But I think what happens
is that everybody

00:42:01.490 --> 00:42:03.420
goes at the same time.

00:42:03.420 --> 00:42:09.200
So if you go during the peak,
Thanksgiving, Christmas,

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:10.107
the holidays here.

00:42:10.107 --> 00:42:11.190
I don't know, when you go?

00:42:11.190 --> 00:42:12.600
What time-- Christmas.

00:42:12.600 --> 00:42:14.560
So what ends up-- first
of, all Argentines

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:16.440
don't like to work at Christmas.

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:18.330
So that might have
been a problem.

00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:20.530
But even if you
go that week, they

00:42:20.530 --> 00:42:23.938
get booked up so, so early.

00:42:23.938 --> 00:42:25.930
Yeah, it is a problem.

00:42:25.930 --> 00:42:27.850
Maybe there's not
enough wineries,

00:42:27.850 --> 00:42:30.240
although there's
over 1,000 wineries.

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:33.390
But give me your name--
next time-- wait.

00:42:33.390 --> 00:42:36.020
Anybody here, I have
this rule that anybody

00:42:36.020 --> 00:42:38.560
who comes to my talk is VIP.

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:40.880
Especially somebody
who reads my book.

00:42:40.880 --> 00:42:44.780
So if it's signed by me,
it's even more of a plus.

